Enclosing class:
JsEvent
public static class JsEvent.Member
extends DOM2Event.Event.Prototype.Member

An opaque class representing members of its enclosing opaque type.

Note that, this class is opaque but its constructors are all internal. This class and the subclasses of this class are used to declare either opaque public instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or the opaque public static fields of other opaque types while their constructors are used to define the fields inside opaque classes. Under either circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque fields of opaque types are resolved by re-compilers directly based on the field names.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be created in the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on operations accessing that kind of class objects. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque instance field declared by this class in Var.Member or its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
q.m
where m is the identifier of the field name and q is the identifier resolved from the instance of the enclosing member. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque static field declared by this class in opaque types other than Var.Member and its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
m
where m is the identifier of the field name. And re-compilers must report error on the access to opaque fields declared by this class under any other circumstances.

Field Detail

bubbles

public final Value.Boolean.Member bubbles

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object refers to a read-only boolean value that is true, if the event is of a type that bubbles unless JsEvent.stopPropagation() is called on the event, or false otherwise.

The property is defined by the DOM Level 2 Events standard.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

currentTarget

public final JsObject.Member currentTarget

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object is read-only reference to the JsElement, JsDocument, or JsWindow object that is currently handling this event. During capturing and bubbling, it is different from JsEvent.target property.

The property is defined by the DOM Level 2 Events standard.

timeStamp

public final JsDate.Member timeStamp

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object is read-only reference to a JsDate object representing the date and time at which the event occurred or, more precisely, at which the JsEvent object was created. Implementations are not required to provide valid time data in this field, and if they do not, the JsDate.getTime() method of the JsDate object should return 0.

The property is defined by the DOM Level 2 Events standard.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

eventPhase

public final Value.Number.Member eventPhase

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object refers to a read-only number indicating the current phase of event propagation. The legal value of the property is JsEvent.CAPTURING_PHASE, JsEvent.AT_TARGET, or JsEvent.BUBBLING_PHASE representing the capturing phase, normal event dispatch, and the bubbling phase respectively.

The property is defined by the DOM Level 2 Events standard.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object is read-only reference to the name of the event that the JsEvent object represents. This is the name under which the event handler was registered, or the name of the event-handler property with the leading "on" removed.

button

public final Value.Integer.Member button

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object is reference to an integer value. For mouse events, the bit mask value specifies which mouse button or buttons were pressed. The 1 bit is set if the left button was pressed; The 2 bit is set if the right button was pressed; and the 4 bit is set if the middle button, of a three-button mouse, was pressed.

Note that the property is IE-Specific.

1.0

keyCode

public final Value.Integer.Member keyCode

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object is reference to an integer value representing the unicode character code generated by the key that was struck for "keypress" events. For "keydown" and "keyup" events, it represents the virtual key code of the key that was struck. Virtual key codes may be dependent on the keyboard layout in use.

Note that the property is IE-Specific.

charCode

public final Value.Number.Member charCode

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsEvent object refers to a read-only integer value specifying the unicode encoding of the printable character (if any) generated by a "keypress" event. This property is 0 for non-printable function keys and is not used for "keydown" and "keyup" events. Use JsGlobal.String.fromCharCode(Object) to convert this property to a string.

Note that the property is IE-Specific.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.
Constructor Detail

JsEvent.Member

public JsEvent.Member(JsObject.Member q,
                      Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member based on a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque instance fields declared in the declaring class of this constructor itself or its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or its subclasses are resolved by re-compilers directly to their names appending to the name resolved from the specified qualifying member with a dot in between.

Parameters:
q - A qualifying member
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.

JsEvent.Member

public JsEvent.Member(Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member without a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque static fields, declared in opaque types other than the declaring class of this constructor itself and its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque static fields of opaque types are generally resolved by re-compilers directly to identifiers of their names.

Parameters:
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.
